## Summary
Add an interactive DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph) renderer page serving as a visualization tool for tracking compute/infra epic work breakdowns in the Phenotype project.

## Context
The DAG renderer provides a visual way to understand task dependencies, status distribution, and workflow progression across epics. This is the implementation of Epic F unit F24 — a foundational piece for the DAG foundation and automation tooling. The renderer reads a structured JSON definition and produces an interactive SVG graph that supports the full lifecycle of work tracking.

## Changes
- New `/dag` route in the projects-landing Astro site under `src/pages/dag/index.astro`
- Vanilla JS client-side DAG renderer implementing longest-path layering, cubic bezier edge routing, and SVG-based rendering
- Sample DAG data file (`data/dag-data.json`) defining the Epic F work breakdown (15 nodes, 18 edges)
- Comprehensive test suite (9 tests) covering data integrity, topological correctness, and status distribution
- Build-time status summary in the page header with per-status counts
- Interactive info panel showing node dependencies and dependents on click

### Key Implementation Details
- **Zero external dependencies** — all rendering uses plain DOM APIs and SVG (no D3.js, no React, no canvas libraries)
- **Automatic layout** implements longest-path layering with centered horizontal positioning per layer
- **Edge routing** uses cubic bezier curves for smooth, readable connections between layers with SVG arrow markers
- **Interaction model**: drag on empty SVG area to pan, mouse wheel to zoom (0.2x–5x), click nodes to select with yellow highlight
- **Status colors**: green (completed), blue (in-progress), gray (pending), red (failed) — with fill/stroke/text variants for readability
- **Embedded JSON** at build time via Astro's frontmatter; client script reads from a `<script type="application/json">` tag

## Use Cases
- Track progress across any DAG-structured workflow (epics, projects, task graphs)
- Visualize dependencies between tasks to identify bottlenecks
- Present status distribution to stakeholders at a glance
- Serve as a reusable renderer for future DAG-based tooling (execution engine, CI pipeline visualization)

## Testing
```bash
# Run the data integrity and topology tests
cd sites/projects-landing
bun test tests/dag-renderer.test.ts

# Build the full site to verify compilation
bun run build

# Verify the dag page is generated
ls dist/dag/index.html
```

## Area
compute-infra
